Feb 15 2008 	Great hotel a little rough round the edges	Lovely clean, new decor and nice sized rooms in a fairly central location. Great access to a variety of restaurants and bars and the Michelin starred Quinlon Indian restaurant next door is well worth a visit. Authentic Indian food in that food is served with a sauce on the side, rather than meat and veg served up altogether in a saucey squodge as we like to serve it in Indian restaurants in this country.Having said that, I would advise persons of the female persuasion who wish to apply makeup, to take a hand mirror to the hotel as the bathroom mirror is at chest height, and behind the sinks. It was v difficult applying mascara from a crouching, leaning forward position.In addition, try to avoid taking the car if poss (or at least taking a nice car.) We took our sports car and were enthusiastically told the doorman would park it for us. Yeah, he would park it somwhere out on the main street as it was a Sunday and so the parking was free there on a Sunday, then he would move it to the NCP on Monday AM. This would have been fine for our old hatchback, but not the new sporty number thanks. We asked if the doorman could park the car in the NCP straightaway as we'd rather pay than leave the car on the street, but our request seemed to be forgotten so we went and parked the car ourselves. The NCP is a fairly substantial walk away from the hotel and it is also worth noting that it was very difficult manouevering the car outside the hotel, as it is up a private, dead end side road, about 5' wide, necessitating a 15 point turn to get out of the street. Look out for those alloys being kerbed!!Oh yes and we made our booking on the internet. Next day, we received an e-mail asking if we wanted a smoking or non-smoking room. We replied non-smoking. When we arrived, we found ashtrays and matches in our room and a note on the door saying the room had been designated a smoking room. When we checked out and we were asked whether everything was alright, we said it was, but mentioned that we'd been given a smoking room, when we'd asked for non-smoking. We were told that all the rooms were smoking and they didn't have non-smoking rooms per se, but if they knew that non-smokers were arriving, they could be given rooms that smelled less of smoke than others. Eh?????Thankfully, our room didn't smell of smoke, and overall, despite all the whining I've done here, I would stay here again. I'd just be prepared for the little idiosyncracies!	
Feb 11 2008 	A super family location. hotel is no longer pristine	I had stayed at this property last summer with my family of 5 plus my two sisters in law. (total of 7)My wife and I were going to London last summer for a family holiday with our 3 little girls (Ages 6, 4 and 2) and to make my life easier I decided to bring my wifes two sisters. I had stayed at Claridges and the Four Seasons and was looking for a family friendly suite with 3 bedrooms.I couldnt find what I was looking for at either of these and came accross this property. I contacted them by phone and they were very helpful. I made arrangements for the newly refurbished 3 bedroom apartment.When we arrived I was told that wasnt available and they had instead a 1 bedroom apartment and a two bedrrom apartment that could be conjoined. I wasnt happy as I had made specfic phones calls in advance to ensure my holiday would be as expected. Once we were shown to the combo apartment I decided to go with it. It gave us an extra living room which worked out super. The way the place was set up we had about a 50 foot hallway with all the rooms running off it including two kitchens, two living rooms, three bedrooms and three washrooms. We paid about $2000.00 Canadian per night for 5 nights including all the taxes. This did not include any of our meals. I was comfortable spending $10,000 for the week based on what I recieved and the location. This may seem like a lot but I was very happy from a value standpoint.The property was a little musty but so are most of the old properties in London. There was quite a bit of noise every morning when they were dumping glass into a dumpster below our 4th floor window. This only seemed to wake me.The kitchens were excellent and well stocked including washer/dryer. There was a great little food store around the corner so I could stock up on ice cream and milk and bread and other little items. The location was terrific (A short walk to buckingham palace and some beautiful parks) and so was the staff. The head butler couldnt do enough for us. The concierge also went out of their way to help. I tipped everyone 20 pounds so that didnt hurt.The hotel had many room service options and the food was excellent. (The kids were usually tired at the end of the day so room service was great) The dover sole was excellent. Maybe $100 but it was great.The rooms could use some updated furnishings and carpets but in general I had a wonderful holiday so maybe thats why i didnt mind a bit of wear. I think I will stay here again when I go back to London with my family.	
